The above plots presents visualization of odds given by 5 different bookmakers for 5 different cases for 2 different types of bet. The bar charts indicates pca of 5 different bookmakers for under odds, over odd, winning odds, losing odds, and tie odds respectively. Wee see tthat there are variations among bookmakers. Pinnacle and Sportingbet have the lowest variances whereas, unibet, youwin and Tipico has a greater variance. However, all of the bookmakers show a similar trend which is decreasing variance when from comp.1 to comp.5. This means that their final odds given for five different oddtypes show a similar behaviour. 5x5 graphs sets are the representation of finall odds for each bookmaker. #include=FALSE doesn't write the code on your document
#eval=TRUE runs the code during knitting process
require(data.table)
require(anytime)
require (MASS)
matches=readRDS ('/Users/esinakgul/Documents/BOUN/4-1/IE 582/HOMEWORK/Homework 1/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_matches.rds')

matches[,c("HomeGoals","AwayGoals"):=tstrsplit(score,':')]
matches$HomeGoals=as.numeric(matches$HomeGoals)
matches[,AwayGoals:=as.numeric(AwayGoals)]

matches=matches[complete.cases(matches)]

matches=matches[,results:='0']



matches=matches[,TotalGoals:=HomeGoals+AwayGoals]

matches[HomeGoals>AwayGoals, results:='Win']
matches[HomeGoals<AwayGoals, results:='Lose']
matches[HomeGoals==AwayGoals, results:='Tie']


tiegames=matches[results=='Tie']
setnames(tiegames, old=c("TotalGoals"), new=c("TotalGoals_TieGame"))
tiegames=tiegames[,index:=1:791]
Lostgames=matches[results=='Lose']
setnames(Lostgames, old=c("TotalGoals"), new=c("TotalGoals_LostGame"))
Lostgames=Lostgames[,index:=1:918]
Wongames=matches[results=='Win']
setnames(Wongames, old=c("TotalGoals"), new=c("TotalGoals_WonGame"))
Wongames=Wongames[,index:=1:1420]


par(mfrow=c(1,3))
single_winning=Wongames[,TotalGoals_WonGame]
pca_winning=princomp(single_winning)
plot(pca_winning)

single_lost=Lostgames[,TotalGoals_LostGame]
pca_lost=princomp(single_lost)
plot(pca_lost)

single_tie=tiegames[,TotalGoals_TieGame]
pca_tie=princomp(single_tie)
plot(pca_tie)

winning_results=Wongames[,TotalGoals_WonGame,index]
losing_results=Lostgames[,TotalGoals_LostGame,index]
tie_results=tiegames[,TotalGoals_TieGame,index]

merged_matches=merge(winning_results,losing_results, by='index')
merged_matches=merge(merged_matches, tie_results, by='index')
merged_matches=merged_matches[,index:=NULL]
merged_pca=princomp(merged_matches)
par(mfrow=c(2,3))
plot(merged_pca)


plot(winning_results, main="Winning Results", xlab="Index of Matches")
plot(losing_results,main="Losing Results", xlab="Index of Matches")
plot(tie_results,xlab="Index of Matches", main="Tie Results")

The above bar graphs represents pca for the match result of win, loss and tie for the home team. First of all single pcas are performed since the size of the sets are not equal. Alltough pcas of won and lost matches have almost the same variance, tie matches have a greater variance. Next, I combined the results to see how pca changes with the number of data. Winning matches were the ones with the greates number of data. So the reduction in this data set resulted in a great deviation in the pca result. Following that a representation of match numbers according the result is visualized. We see that most of the matches have ended below a total score of 6. However, there are also some matches with a total score of 8 and 10.
